{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.12,0,0.52,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112162"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94227"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9294"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112162"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a painless swelling in her right groin that is more noticeable when she stands. She reports no fevers, weight loss, change in bowel habit, or local skin changes. There is no associated trauma or preceding strenuous activity. She has a medical history of hypertension, atrial fibrillation and excision of a melanoma from her right leg two years ago with clear margins. Her regular medications are perindopril and warfarin. She recently completed a short course of antibiotics for a chest infection. She is independent with activities of daily living and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min and irregularly irregular, blood pressure 136/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. There is a soft, non-tender, non-reducible swelling in the right groin that lies below and lateral to the pubic tubercle and below the inguinal ligament, with no cough impulse. There is no overlying erythema and the femoral pulse is palpable. The contralateral groin is normal and there is no palpable lymphadenopathy. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. No investigations have been performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the groin","CT abdomen and pelvis","Fine needle aspiration","Surgical repair","Oncology clinic referral"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGroin lumps require careful localisation relative to the inguinal ligament. A lump that lies below the inguinal ligament and lateral to the pubic tubercle in an older woman strongly suggests a femoral hernia. Femoral hernias are frequently irreducible and often lack a cough impulse because of a narrow, rigid neck. They carry a substantial risk of obstruction and strangulation, so once clinically identified, timely operative management is preferred over prolonged investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrgent referral for\u003Cstrong\u003E surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E is the best next step because the clinical features localise the swelling to the femoral canal, the lump is irreducible, and femoral hernias have a high risk of incarceration and strangulation. Delaying for imaging offers little additional diagnostic yield and risks adverse outcomes; elective or semi-urgent repair is advised even if asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the groin\u003C/strong\u003E can help when the diagnosis is uncertain or the examination is challenging. However, in this scenario the swelling\u2019s position below the inguinal ligament with irreducibility makes a femoral hernia highly likely, and imaging would delay definitive management without altering the plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful if there is diagnostic uncertainty, concern for malignancy, or suspected complications such as bowel obstruction. Here there are no systemic symptoms, no obstructive features, and clear clinical localisation to the femoral canal; routine computed tomography would not change management and would delay surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for a suspected hernia and risks injury to vascular structures in the femoral triangle. Aspiration is reserved for cystic masses or lymph nodes when malignancy or infection is suspected, which is not supported by the history or examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOncology clinic referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated despite the history of treated melanoma with clear margins and no features of local recurrence or nodal disease. The lump\u2019s location below the inguinal ligament and its hernia characteristics make metastatic lymphadenopathy unlikely; surgical assessment is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Femoral hernias typically present as a groin lump below the inguinal ligament, are often irreducible, and have a high risk of obstruction and strangulation.","In an older woman with a clinically apparent femoral hernia, definitive surgical referral is indicated rather than delay for imaging.","Absence of a cough impulse does not exclude a hernia and is common in femoral hernias due to a narrow neck."],"references":["Hamilton W, Pascoe J, John J, et al. Diagnosing groin lumps. BMJ 2021; 372:n578 http://dx.doi.org/10.1136/bmj.n578","Fitzgibbons RJ, Armour Forse R. Groin Hernias in Adults. N Engl J Med 2015; 372:756-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17772"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17772"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9bc8b0e7-dce6-4d0e-b9fa-b3be271f3197.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9bc8b0e7-dce6-4d0e-b9fa-b3be271f3197.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94227"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T09:11:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T22:25:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112162"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"re